        <p>I've actually found that this is a hard number to pin down. Here's what I can tell you:</p>
    {% endslide %}
    {% slide %}
        <p>In 2018, Mozilla reported that internet data centres alone produced <strong>roughly the same carbon emissions as {% ext "https://internethealthreport.org/2018/the-internet-uses-more-electricity-than/" %}the airline industry{% endext %}</strong> - about 2% of total emissions.</p>
        <p>This number doesn't factor in all the other devices that form the client end of the web - phones, laptops, personal computers, TVs, watches, {% ext "https://www.pcmag.com/reviews/brita-infinity-wi-fi-connected-pitcher" %}water pitchers{% endext %}, {% ext "https://www.lavviebot.com/en/home.html" %}litterboxes{% endext %}, {% ext "https://www.allure.com/story/kerastase-hair-coach" %}hairbrushes{% endext %}, et al.</p>
    {% endslide %}
    {% slide %}
        <p>At the beginning of 2019, French "post-carbon economy think tank" The Shift Project estimated the total share of global emissions created by the internet to be {% ext "https://theshiftproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/Lean-ICT-Report_The-Shift-Project_2019.pdf" %}3.7%{% endext %} of the {% ext "https://www.iea.org/data-and-statistics/charts/co2-emissions-from-energy-combustion-and-industrial-processes-1900-2021" %}36.1 billion metric tons{% endext %} emitted globally, (for a total of about 1.3 billion tons), but that number still doesn't capture the seismic changes in the world over the past three years.</p>
    {% endslide %}
    {% slide %}
        <p>Carbon emissions dipped in 2020, only to rebound in 2021, while work-from-home, streaming and "{% ext "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web3" %}web3{%endext%}" technologies made major changes to the internet's energy consumption. But by how much?</p>
        <p>To answer those questions, let's look at some of the big movers in bandwidth over the past two years.</p>
    {% endslide %}
{% endsection %}
